node.text:
Black History Month ended yesterday but Black History is created daily. Woman’s History Month started today, but women create history daily. Our desire to highlight the “special” events of those two marginalized groups in two months is unfortunate, as both should be represented throughout the entire year. As we take a step back and analyze wealth and income in the U.S. we find evidence of staggering racial disparities. At $171,000, the net worth of a typical white family is nearly ten times greater than that of a Black family ($17,150) in 2016. For me, that statistic means one of two things: 1) White people are 10x better than blacks, or 2) compounding effects of inequality and discrimination, paired with differences in power and opportunity tracing back to the nation’s inception is the cause for the difference.

If you believe the former, please unfollow me! If you believe the latter, we understand how the Black-White wealth gap reflects a society that has not and does not afford equality of opportunity to all its citizens.

Efforts by Black Americans to build wealth can be traced back throughout American history. But these efforts have been impeded in a host of ways, beginning with 246 years of chattel slavery and followed by Congressional mismanagement of the Freedman’s Savings Bank (which left 61,144 depositors with losses of nearly $3 million in 1874), the violent massacre decimating Tulsa’s Greenwood District in 1921 (a population of 10,000 that thrived as the epicenter of African American business and culture, commonly referred to as “Black Wall Street”), and discriminatory policies throughout the 20th century including the Jim Crow Era’s “Black Codes” strictly limiting opportunity in many southern states, the GI bill, the New Deal’s Fair Labor Standards Act’s exemption of domestic agricultural and service occupations, and redlining. The reality is, wealth was taken from these communities before it had the opportunity to grow.

We’re here to change that but we cannot do it alone, please comment and share if you’re empowered to make that change.

There’s nothing wrong with Black People that ending racism can’t solve. - @andreperryedu

This video is from a hurt young man from my hometown in Milwaukee. 4 years ago, Milwaukee was Minneapolis. Until we start to fix the ROOT of the issue, these things will continue to happen. People will continue to be hurt and that pain will transform into a reaction that no one wants to see.

I am a black man, and to be real, at times I think I can avoid these situations. I’m an optimist that wants to believe that I could get out of a situation if one ever presented itself. But the reality is.. I can’t. My  father, uncle, cousins, friends or I could’ve been George, and there isn’t anything we can do about it.

I’m personally sick of this shit, sick of having to have these conversations, sick of people having to reaching out and check on me. The fact of the matter is, there isn’t ANYTHING I could do to change this reality.

For anyone who doesn’t HAVE to deal with the reality I described above. Just know that’s privilege, every has it in some way shape or form, not all privilege is bad, but at the very least, it needs to be acknowledged. #rip #georgefloyd #blacklivesmatter #racism #equity #minneapolis

I'm Proud to have Rule Enterprises partner with other Commercial Real Estate Titians to identify and remove the obstacles facing minority owners and operators in the CRE industry.

The CRE Diversity Initiative is an alliance amongst some of CRE's top owners, operators, and financiers, and it's intended to drive sustainable change across the industry.

It’s important for us to do OUR job and hold people within our community accountable. However it’s just as important to connect with the people who currently hold the power, meet them where they are, effectively communicate the systematic issues and hold them accountable. #BeTheChange #CommercialRealEstate

node.text:
Black History Month ended yesterday but Black History is created daily. Woman’s History Month started today, but women create history daily. Our desire to highlight the “special” events of those two marginalized groups in two months is unfortunate, as both should be represented throughout the entire year. As we take a step back and analyze wealth and income in the U.S. we find evidence of staggering racial disparities. At $171,000, the net worth of a typical white family is nearly ten times greater than that of a Black family ($17,150) in 2016. For me, that statistic means one of two things: 1) White people are 10x better than blacks, or 2) compounding effects of inequality and discrimination, paired with differences in power and opportunity tracing back to the nation’s inception is the cause for the difference.

If you believe the former, please unfollow me! If you believe the latter, we understand how the Black-White wealth gap reflects a society that has not and does not afford equality of opportunity to all its citizens.

Efforts by Black Americans to build wealth can be traced back throughout American history. But these efforts have been impeded in a host of ways, beginning with 246 years of chattel slavery and followed by Congressional mismanagement of the Freedman’s Savings Bank (which left 61,144 depositors with losses of nearly $3 million in 1874), the violent massacre decimating Tulsa’s Greenwood District in 1921 (a population of 10,000 that thrived as the epicenter of African American business and culture, commonly referred to as “Black Wall Street”), and discriminatory policies throughout the 20th century including the Jim Crow Era’s “Black Codes” strictly limiting opportunity in many southern states, the GI bill, the New Deal’s Fair Labor Standards Act’s exemption of domestic agricultural and service occupations, and redlining. The reality is, wealth was taken from these communities before it had the opportunity to grow.

We’re here to change that but we cannot do it alone, please comment and share if you’re empowered to make that change.

node.text:
The building behind me is a new construction 89-unit development project that I’m building less than a mile away from where I was raised. The goal was to slow the rapid pace of gentrification in the area by creating quality housing and maintain affordable rents. God willing, this summer the goal will be accomplished.

US Bank is my construction lender and this month they’re releasing a Black History Month publication that highlights our partnership. They truly see me as “Black History in the Making” because I’m the first black person they’ve ever given a construction loan to.

I appreciate the applause that may come from that fact, but it’s extremely unfortunate that it took so long. Also, had the owner of the construction company that I hired not made a personal guarantee along side of me, this post wouldn’t exist.

I made that very clear in the write up, and I asked to speak with the CEO of the bank because clearly the parameters need to change. I have a relationship, so the next one would be fairly easy for me, but for the emerging developers you shouldn’t have to wait another 50+ years for that to be a reality.

It’s my mission to eradicate the wealth gap, and I want to bring you all along that journey. I’ve created a google form to create a real estate directory, so we can build our teams across the country. Please click the link in my bio to fill it out and please share it with people in the space. Feel free to text me when you’re done or have any additional comments! 202-918-4820. Let’s all #StriveForGreatness.

Also, special s/o to my Owners Rep/ Construction Manager @m_emem__ with Emem Group for also Living Black History, y’all make sure y’all follow him!
